---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Notion API in Practice: Building a Task Management MCP Tool — Using AI Agents for Real Tasks"
  description="After organizing data, the next step is often to put it into Notion. This page walks through building a small Notion MCP server with three tools — read, create, update — so an AI agent can act on your classroom tasks within a clear, safe boundary."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container ai-agent-notion">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Build Your Own Small Notion MCP — Let AI Touch Notion Inside a Boundary</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          We've already practiced having AI organize CSV and tabular data. But <strong>after the cleanup, there's almost always a next step</strong>: drop the to-do into Notion, flip a task to "In progress," mark a finished item as done. This page turns Notion into a tool an AI agent can use.
        </p>
      </header>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        We're <strong>not going to use an off-the-shelf Notion MCP</strong> here. Instead, we'll build a small classroom-style Notion MCP server ourselves. The benefits:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>We get to <strong>decide what the AI can do</strong></li>
        <li>And <strong>what the AI can't do</strong></li>
        <li>The smaller the tool, the <strong>clearer its boundary</strong></li>
        <li>The clearer the boundary, the <strong>safer it is to use</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card callout-card--warn">
        <p class="callout-text">
          The Notion API lets external tools read, create, and update Notion data. But <strong>before any call you must create a connection</strong> and share the relevant page or database with it — otherwise the API has no permission. Notion also reminds developers that <strong>the token is a secret</strong>: never hardcode it or commit it to version control.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="detail-heading">Three things, no more</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This Notion tool is <strong>not an all-purpose Notion assistant</strong>. It only does three things:
      </p>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">list_classroom_tasks</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">read classroom tasks</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">create_classroom_task</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">add a new classroom task</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">update_task_status</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">update a task's status</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Three actions are enough to practice the basics of the Notion API while <strong>keeping the tool small from day one</strong>.
      </p>

      <!-- ============ PART 1 ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 1</span>
        <span class="part-text">Build a practice database in Notion</span>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Before writing any Python or MCP code, we need to set up a database in Notion. A Notion database is <strong>a slightly smarter table</strong> — each row holds field data and can also open into its own page. We recommend a <strong>Table database</strong> here: it's the closest thing to an ordinary table and the most natural fit for read / create / update practice.
      </p>

      <!-- STEP 1 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 1</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Create a new page</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Open Notion and click <strong>"Database"</strong> in the left sidebar. Use this page name:
      </p>
      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>課堂任務管理 (Classroom Tasks)</code></pre>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This page will hold the task data we'll work with later.
      </p>

      <!-- STEP 2 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 2</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Create a Table database</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Inside the new page, choose <strong>"Start with a database"</strong>, then pick the <strong>"Empty database"</strong> option from the menu.
      </p>

      <!-- STEP 3 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 3</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Confirm the database name</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Make sure the database is called <strong>「課堂任務管理」</strong>. If Notion auto-creates an unnamed database, rename it to this title.
      </p>
      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          The name is mostly <strong>for human readers</strong>. What the program actually uses is Notion's <code>data_source_id</code>, not the database name.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 4 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 4</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Create the columns</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Add the columns the database needs, exactly as listed below:
      </p>

      <div class="csv-table-wrapper">
        <table class="csv-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Column name</th>
              <th>Property type</th>
              <th>Notes</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>任務名稱</td><td>Text</td><td>The task name</td></tr>
            <tr><td>類型</td><td>Select</td><td>Which category the task belongs to</td></tr>
            <tr><td>狀態</td><td>Select</td><td>Current processing status</td></tr>
            <tr><td>優先順序</td><td>Select</td><td>High / Medium / Low</td></tr>
            <tr><td>截止日</td><td>Date</td><td>When the task is due</td></tr>
            <tr><td>來源</td><td>Text</td><td>Where the task came from</td></tr>
            <tr><td>備註</td><td>Text</td><td>Additional notes</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="callout-card callout-card--warn">
        <p class="callout-text">
          <strong>Column names must match exactly.</strong> If the program uses「任務名稱」, don't shorten it to「任務」or「名稱」in Notion. The Notion API looks columns up <strong>by name</strong>; a mismatch means the program won't find the right field.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 5 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 5</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Configure the Select options</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        A few columns aren't free-text — they use <strong>fixed options</strong>. This reduces the inconsistency problem (one person writes「處理中」, another「進行中」, another「正在處理」 — and the program can't tell). So we lock the options down up front. For each column below, use <strong>"Edit property"</strong> and add the options:
      </p>

      <h4 class="example-heading">「狀態」 column (3 options)</h4>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>待確認 (Pending)</li>
        <li>處理中 (In progress)</li>
        <li>已完成 (Done)</li>
      </ul>

      <h4 class="example-heading">「類型」 column (4 options)</h4>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>教學準備 (Teaching prep)</li>
        <li>學生回覆 (Student response)</li>
        <li>行政事項 (Admin)</li>
        <li>閱讀材料 (Reading material)</li>
      </ul>

      <h4 class="example-heading">「優先順序」 column (3 options)</h4>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>高 (High)</li>
        <li>中 (Medium)</li>
        <li>低 (Low)</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          These fixed options will line up with the Python program later —<br/>
          the tool <strong>only accepts these values</strong>.<br/>
          This isn't restricting the AI; it's <strong>making the data more stable</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 6 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 6</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Add some sample rows</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Once the columns are in place, add a few rows manually:
      </p>

      <div class="csv-table-wrapper">
        <table class="csv-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>任務名稱</th>
              <th>類型</th>
              <th>狀態</th>
              <th>優先順序</th>
              <th>截止日</th>
              <th>來源</th>
              <th>備註</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>確認下週課堂公告</td><td>教學準備</td><td>待確認</td><td>高</td><td>2026-03-20</td><td>課程安排</td><td>需要確認教室、時間與提醒內容</td></tr>
            <tr><td>整理學生提問</td><td>學生回覆</td><td>處理中</td><td>中</td><td>2026-03-22</td><td>課堂回饋</td><td>先整理重複問題</td></tr>
            <tr><td>準備閱讀材料摘要</td><td>閱讀材料</td><td>待確認</td><td>中</td><td>2026-03-25</td><td>閱讀清單</td><td>先產生摘要草稿，不直接發給學生</td></tr>
            <tr><td>回覆活動證明申請</td><td>行政事項</td><td>已完成</td><td>低</td><td>2026-03-18</td><td>活動報名表</td><td>已確認名單</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        These rows are what later exercises will use. It's a small dataset, but a useful one — it covers <strong>different statuses, types, and priorities</strong>, plus tasks that can be updated.
      </p>

      <!-- ============ PART 2 ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 2</span>
        <span class="part-text">Set up a connection to the Notion API</span>
      </div>

      <h2 class="detail-heading">First: database vs. data source</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In the newer Notion API design, <strong>database and data source are separate concepts</strong>. A simple way to think about it:
      </p>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Database</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">Behaves more like a <strong>shell or container</strong></span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Data source</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">The actual <strong>table that holds each row</strong></span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Page</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">Each row in the API is treated as a "page"</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Notion's docs note that starting from <strong>API version 2025-09-03</strong>, most operations that used to take <code>database_id</code> now take <code>data_source_id</code>; <code>2026-03-11</code> is also available as an API header. The examples on this page use the <strong>new data_source_id form</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So we need two key pieces of information:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><code>NOTION_API_KEY</code></li>
        <li><code>NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID</code></li>
      </ul>

      <!-- STEP A -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP A</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Create a Notion connection</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For Python to reach Notion, we first create a connection. From the workspace switcher in the top-left of Notion:
      </p>
      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>Settings → Connections → Develop or manage integrations → Create new internal integration</code></pre>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Name it <code>Classroom Tool</code>. Then make sure it has at least these capabilities:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Read content</li>
        <li>Update content</li>
        <li>Insert content</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        <strong>Don't enable more than you need.</strong> This tool only reads, creates, and updates tasks — there's no need for delete, and no need to manage the entire workspace.
      </p>

      <!-- STEP B -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP B</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Share the database with the connection</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        After creating the connection, <strong>it isn't usable yet</strong>. You need to go back to the「課堂任務管理」database and share it with the connection — otherwise API requests will fail.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Open「課堂任務管理」 in Notion, then:
      </p>
      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>Top-right ⋯ → Connections → Select Classroom Tool</code></pre>

      <div class="callout-card callout-card--warn">
        <p class="callout-text">
          <strong>This step is critical.</strong> A lot of Notion API errors aren't bugs in the code — they're <strong>databases that haven't been shared with the connection</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP C -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP C</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Find the data source ID</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The simplest path: in the database's top-right area, click the slider icon labelled <strong>"Settings"</strong> (left of "New"), then:
      </p>
      <ol class="numbered-list">
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Click <strong>"Manage data sources"</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Click the <strong>⋯</strong> next to「課堂任務管理」</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Copy the <strong>data source ID</strong></span></li>
      </ol>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Set this ID aside — we'll need it shortly.
      </p>

      <!-- ============ PART 3 ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 3</span>
        <span class="part-text">Write a small MCP server</span>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP I -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP I</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Create the project folder</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In VS Code, create a new project folder named <code>notion-classroom-tool</code>. The structure can start as:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>notion-classroom-tool
├─ notion_classroom_server.py
├─ .env
└─ .gitignore</code></pre>

      <!-- STEP II -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP II</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Create .env and .gitignore</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Put these in <code>.env</code>:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>NOTION_API_KEY=your_notion_connection_token
NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID=your_data_source_id
NOTION_VERSION=2026-03-11</code></pre>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>The <code>notion_connection_token</code> appears as <strong>"Internal Integration Secret"</strong> on the Classroom Tool page after creation — click "Show" to reveal it before copying</li>
        <li>The <code>data_source_id</code> is the one you just copied in STEP C</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card callout-card--warn">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Important:<br/>
          ✗ Don't <strong>hardcode the API key</strong> in Python.<br/>
          ✗ Don't <strong>push .env to GitHub</strong>.<br/>
          ✗ Don't <strong>paste the token into public docs</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        <code>.gitignore</code> can be:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>.env
.venv/
__pycache__/</code></pre>

      <!-- STEP III -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP III</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Install dependencies</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In the VS Code terminal, initialize the project:
      </p>
      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>uv init</code></pre>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Activate the virtual environment, then add the packages:
      </p>
      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code>uv add "mcp[cli]" python-dotenv requests</code></pre>

      <!-- STEP IV -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP IV</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Which tools are we building?</h2>
      </div>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">list_classroom_tasks</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Reads Notion tasks</strong></span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">create_classroom_task</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Creates a new Notion task</strong></span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">update_task_status</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Updates a task's status</strong></span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card callout-card--warn">
        <p class="callout-text">
          We're <strong>deliberately not building a delete tool</strong>. Delete is a high-risk action and not appropriate for this practice.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP V -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP V</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Write the MCP server</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Place the following in <code>notion_classroom_server.py</code>:
      </p>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">notion_classroom_server.py — full source</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand (~220 lines)</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">from typing import Optional
import os
import requests
from dotenv import load_dotenv
from mcp.server.fastmcp import FastMCP

load_dotenv()

mcp = FastMCP("notion-classroom")

NOTION_API_KEY = os.getenv("NOTION_API_KEY")
NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID = os.getenv("NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID")
NOTION_VERSION = os.getenv("NOTION_VERSION", "2026-03-11")

NOTION_BASE_URL = "https://api.notion.com/v1"

ALLOWED_STATUS = ["待確認", "處理中", "已完成"]
ALLOWED_CATEGORY = ["教學準備", "學生回覆", "行政事項", "閱讀材料"]
ALLOWED_PRIORITY = ["高", "中", "低"]


def notion_headers() -> dict:
    if not NOTION_API_KEY:
        raise ValueError("Missing NOTION_API_KEY. Check your .env file.")

    return {
        "Authorization": f"Bearer {NOTION_API_KEY}",
        "Notion-Version": NOTION_VERSION,
        "Content-Type": "application/json",
    }


def notion_request(method: str, path: str, payload: Optional[dict] = None) -> dict:
    try:
        response = requests.request(
            method=method,
            url=f"{NOTION_BASE_URL}{path}",
            headers=notion_headers(),
            json=payload,
            timeout=20,
        )

        if response.status_code >= 400:
            try:
                detail = response.json()
            except Exception:
                detail = response.text

            return {
                "ok": False,
                "status_code": response.status_code,
                "message": "Notion API returned an error.",
                "detail": detail,
            }

        return {
            "ok": True,
            "data": response.json(),
        }

    except requests.RequestException as error:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "Failed to reach the Notion API.",
            "detail": str(error),
        }


def get_title(properties: dict, name: str) -> str:
    title_items = properties.get(name, {}).get("title", [])
    return "".join(item.get("plain_text", "") for item in title_items)


def get_select(properties: dict, name: str) -> str:
    value = properties.get(name, {}).get("select")
    if not value:
        return ""
    return value.get("name", "")


def get_date(properties: dict, name: str) -> str:
    value = properties.get(name, {}).get("date")
    if not value:
        return ""
    return value.get("start", "")


def get_rich_text(properties: dict, name: str) -> str:
    text_items = properties.get(name, {}).get("rich_text", [])
    return "".join(item.get("plain_text", "") for item in text_items)


def page_to_task(page: dict) -> dict:
    properties = page.get("properties", {})

    return {
        "page_id": page.get("id", ""),
        "url": page.get("url", ""),
        "任務名稱": get_title(properties, "任務名稱"),
        "類型": get_select(properties, "類型"),
        "狀態": get_select(properties, "狀態"),
        "優先順序": get_select(properties, "優先順序"),
        "截止日": get_date(properties, "截止日"),
        "來源": get_rich_text(properties, "來源"),
        "備註": get_rich_text(properties, "備註"),
    }


@mcp.tool()
def list_classroom_tasks(status: str = "待確認", limit: int = 10) -> dict:
    """
    Read classroom tasks from Notion.

    status can be: 全部, 待確認, 處理中, 已完成.
    limit is the max number of rows returned, between 1 and 20.
    """
    if not NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "Missing NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID. Check your .env file.",
        }

    if status not in ["全部"] + ALLOWED_STATUS:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "Status not allowed.",
            "allowed_status": ["全部"] + ALLOWED_STATUS,
        }

    if limit &lt; 1 or limit &gt; 20:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "limit must be between 1 and 20.",
        }

    payload = {
        "page_size": limit,
    }

    if status != "全部":
        payload["filter"] = {
            "property": "狀態",
            "select": {
                "equals": status,
            },
        }

    result = notion_request(
        "POST",
        f"/data_sources/{NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID}/query",
        payload,
    )

    if not result["ok"]:
        return result

    pages = result["data"].get("results", [])
    tasks = [page_to_task(page) for page in pages]

    return {
        "ok": True,
        "count": len(tasks),
        "tasks": tasks,
    }


@mcp.tool()
def create_classroom_task(
    title: str,
    category: str = "教學準備",
    priority: str = "中",
    due_date: str = "",
    source: str = "",
    note: str = "",
) -> dict:
    """
    Create a classroom task in Notion.

    title is the task name.
    category can be: 教學準備, 學生回覆, 行政事項, 閱讀材料.
    priority can be: 高, 中, 低.
    due_date should use YYYY-MM-DD format, e.g. 2026-03-20.
    """
    if not NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "Missing NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID. Check your .env file.",
        }

    title = title.strip()

    if not title:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "Task name cannot be empty.",
        }

    if len(title) &gt; 80:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "Task name is too long. Keep it under 80 characters.",
        }

    if category not in ALLOWED_CATEGORY:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "Category not allowed.",
            "allowed_category": ALLOWED_CATEGORY,
        }

    if priority not in ALLOWED_PRIORITY:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "Priority not allowed.",
            "allowed_priority": ALLOWED_PRIORITY,
        }

    properties = {
        "任務名稱": {
            "title": [{"text": {"content": title}}],
        },
        "類型": {
            "select": {"name": category},
        },
        "狀態": {
            "select": {"name": "待確認"},
        },
        "優先順序": {
            "select": {"name": priority},
        },
        "來源": {
            "rich_text": [{"text": {"content": source}}],
        },
        "備註": {
            "rich_text": [{"text": {"content": note}}],
        },
    }

    if due_date:
        properties["截止日"] = {
            "date": {"start": due_date},
        }

    payload = {
        "parent": {
            "type": "data_source_id",
            "data_source_id": NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID,
        },
        "properties": properties,
    }

    result = notion_request("POST", "/pages", payload)

    if not result["ok"]:
        return result

    page = result["data"]

    return {
        "ok": True,
        "message": "Notion task created.",
        "page_id": page.get("id", ""),
        "url": page.get("url", ""),
        "任務名稱": title,
        "狀態": "待確認",
    }


@mcp.tool()
def update_task_status(page_id: str, new_status: str) -> dict:
    """
    Update a Notion task's status.

    new_status can only be: 待確認, 處理中, 已完成.
    This tool only updates status — it never modifies the title, date, or notes.
    """
    page_id = page_id.strip()

    if not page_id:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "Missing page_id. Cannot update task.",
        }

    if new_status not in ALLOWED_STATUS:
        return {
            "ok": False,
            "message": "Status not allowed.",
            "allowed_status": ALLOWED_STATUS,
        }

    payload = {
        "properties": {
            "狀態": {
                "select": {"name": new_status},
            },
        },
    }

    result = notion_request("PATCH", f"/pages/{page_id}", payload)

    if not result["ok"]:
        return result

    return {
        "ok": True,
        "message": "Task status updated.",
        "page_id": page_id,
        "new_status": new_status,
    }


if __name__ == "__main__":
    mcp.run()
</code></pre>
        </div>
