      <!-- ============ Section: safety boundary ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">The safety boundaries baked into this tool</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This MCP server has several <strong>intentional restrictions</strong>:
      </p>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label role-item__label--ord">1.</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>No deletes.</strong> Delete is high-risk.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label role-item__label--ord">2.</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>No editing the task name.</strong> Prevents the AI from rewriting what the task means.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label role-item__label--ord">3.</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>No editing the due date.</strong> Dates often involve real-world arrangements and should be confirmed by a human.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label role-item__label--ord">4.</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>No free-form status values.</strong> Status must be one of the fixed options.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label role-item__label--ord">5.</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>New tasks are always created with status「待確認」.</strong> Stops the AI from declaring a brand-new task as done.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          These limits don't make the tool weaker — they <strong>make it more useful for real workflows</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Section: common errors ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Common errors</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If reads fail, the cause is usually one of:
      </p>

      <ol class="numbered-list">
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Wrong <code>NOTION_API_KEY</code> in .env</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Wrong <code>NOTION_DATA_SOURCE_ID</code></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text">The Notion database <strong>wasn't shared with the connection</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">4</span><span class="numbered-list__text">The connection lacks <strong>read or update capabilities</strong></span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">5</span><span class="numbered-list__text">Column names in Notion <strong>don't match the names in the program</strong></span></li>
      </ol>

      <!-- ============ Section: takeaway ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">The most important idea on this page</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This Notion API exercise isn't about <strong>letting the AI control all of Notion</strong>. It's about designing a small, focused set of tools yourself: the smaller the tool, the easier it is to understand, the easier to test, and the easier to set <strong>safety boundaries</strong> on.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Our three tools split responsibility cleanly, and they slot directly into the AI workflow we discussed earlier:
      </p>

      <div class="flow-card">
        <div class="flow-step">Read first (list_classroom_tasks)</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Organize</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Draft when needed (create_classroom_task)</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Human verifies</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--accent">Then update status (update_task_status)</div>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        AI can help operate Notion, but <strong>not every Notion action belongs to the AI</strong>. Starting out, the safer pattern is:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Expose <strong>only the tools you need</strong></li>
        <li>Grant <strong>only the permissions you need</strong></li>
        <li>Let the AI modify <strong>only a small surface</strong></li>
        <li>Reserve <strong>important decisions for human review</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="highlight-card highlight-card--final">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          The benefit of building your own tool isn't<br/>
          "making the AI more powerful."<br/>
          It's <strong>making it clear to yourself what the AI can and can't do inside the boundary you drew</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

